===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|emeraude}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|esmeraude}}, from {{etyl|VL.|en}} {{m|la|*esmaralda}}, {{m|la|*esmaraldus}}, variant of {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|smaragdus}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|σμάραγδος}}, {{m|grc|μάραγδος}}, from a {{etyl|sem|en}} language. Compare {{cog|he|בָּרֶקֶת|tr=bareket}} “emerald, flashing gem”, Akkadian {{m|akk|tr=barruktu, baragtu}}, Arabic بَرْق ''barq'' “lightning” and loanwords with Semitic etymon such as {{cog|sa|मरकत|tr=marakata}} and Persian {{m|fa|زمرد|tr=zomorrod}} (whence Turkish {{m|tr|zümrüt}} and Russian {{m|ru|изумру́д}}).

